{{redirect|Death warrant|the 1990 film|Death Warrant (film)}} {{distinguish|Warrant of execution|writ of execution}} {{globalize/US|date=December 2010}} [[File:Death warrant of Charles I.jpg|thumb|alt=Large hand-written document, coloured yellow with age. There is a block of text at the top, and 59 signatures and red wax seals at the bottom.|thumb|The [[Trial and execution of Charles I|death warrant (1649) of King Charles I of England]] and the [[Seal (emblem)|wax seal]]s of the 59 commissioners.{{efn|In 2011 the death warrant for Charles I was added by [[UNESCO]] to the [[UK Memory of the World Register]] ({{harvnb|UKP: Warrant}}; {{harvnb|UNESCO: Register}})}}]]
{{Criminal procedure (trial)}} An '''execution warrant''' (also called '''death warrant''' or '''black warrant''') is a [[writ]] that authorizes the [[Execution (legal)|execution]] of a judgment of death ([[capital punishment]]) on an individual. An execution [[Warrant (legal)|warrant]] is not to be confused with a "[[License to kill (concept)|license to kill]]", which operates like an [[arrest warrant]] but with [[deadly force]] instead of arrest as the end goal.
== United States of America == In the [[United States]] either a judicial or executive official designated by law issues an execution warrant. This is done when a person, in trial court proceedings, has been sentenced to death, after [[trial (law)|trial]] and [[conviction (law)|conviction]], and usually after appeals are exhausted. Normally when a death warrant is signed and an execution date is set, the condemned person is moved from his or her [[death row]] cell to a death watch cell, which is typically located adjacent to the [[execution chamber]]. Usually, the government agency charged with carrying out an execution, normally the state's [[Department of Corrections]] or the U.S. [[Bureau of Prisons]] in federal cases, has a limited time frame, normally about 60 days, from the date the warrant is signed, to complete the execution process, or the warrant expires and the condemned person is returned to the death row cell, where he or she will await another execution date.
[[Stays of execution]] can be ordered in state cases by the Governor of the state, a trial court, a state appeals court or state Supreme Court or a court in the federal judiciary (including the [[United States Supreme Court]]). In federal death penalty cases the trial court, appeals courts, the United States Supreme Court and [[President of the United States|President]] may grant a stay of execution. In all cases, the stay may be issued at any time, even when the condemned is being prepared for execution.
=== Setting of execution dates by state === {|class="wikitable" |- !width=120px|'''State''' !width=120px|Power !Notes |- |'''[[Capital punishment by the United States federal government|Federal]] |[[United States district court|District Court Judge]] | |---- |'''[[Capital punishment by the United States military|Military]] |[[United States Secretary of the Army|Secretary of the Army]] |The Secretary of the Army, as the designated Department of Defense Corrections Level III executive official, sets the date and location of military executions. The execution date must be at least 60 days after affirmation of the sentence by the [[President of the United States]]. All sentences of death must be personally affirmed, in writing, by the President of the United States before the Secretary of the Army is permitted to set an execution date.<ref>https://fas.org/irp/doddir/army/r190_55.pdf</ref> |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in Alabama|Alabama]] |[[Alabama Supreme Court]] |The sentence shall be executed at any hour on the day set for the execution, not less than 30 nor more than 100 days from the date of sentencing.<ref>http://www.legislature.state.al.us/CodeofAlabama/1975/15-18-82.htm</ref> |---- |'''[[List of individuals executed in Arizona|Arizona]] |[[Arizona Supreme Court]] | |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in Arkansas|Arkansas]] |[[Governor of Arkansas|Governor]] | |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in California|California]] |Trial Court Judge |The execution date shall not be less than 60 days nor more than 90 days from the time of making the order <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leginfo.ca.gov/cgi-bin/waisgate?WAISdocID=56475716183+1+0+0&WAISaction=retrieve|title=WAIS Document Retrieval|work=ca.gov}}</ref> |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in Colorado|Colorado]] |Trial Court Judge | |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in Connecticut|Connecticut]] |Trial Court Judge | On May 22, 2009, the Connecticut General Assembly passed a bill that would abolish the death penalty, although it would not retroactively apply to the eleven current Connecticut death row inmates or those convicted of capital crimes committed before the repeal went into effect. The bill was vetoed by Governor Jodi Rell.
On April 11, 2012, the Connecticut House of Representatives voted to repeal capital punishment for future cases (leaving past death sentences in place). The Connecticut Senate had already voted for the bill, and on April 25 Governor Dannel Malloy signed the bill into law That made Connecticut the 17th state in the US without a death penalty, and the fifth state to abolish capital punishment in five years. In 2015 the state Supreme Court ruled found that applying the death penalty only for past cases was unconstitutional, definitely emptying Connecticut death row. |---- |'''[[List of individuals executed in Delaware|Delaware]] |Trial Court Judge | |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in Florida|Florida]] |[[Governor of Florida|Governor]] |After a stay of execution is dissolved, the Governor must set the new date for execution of the death sentence within 10 days. The Governor can grant stays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leg.state.fl.us/statutes/index.cfm?App_mode=Display_Statute&URL=0900-0999/0922/Sections/0922.052.html|title=Statutes & Constitution :View Statutes : Online Sunshine|work=state.fl.us}}</ref> If a death sentence is not carried out because of unjustified failure of the Governor to issue a warrant, or for any other unjustifiable reason, on application of the Department of Legal Affairs, the Supreme Court shall issue a warrant directing the sentence to be executed during a week designated in the warrant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leg.state.fl.us/statutes/index.cfm?App_mode=Display_Statute&URL=0900-0999/0922/Sections/0922.14.html|title=Statutes & Constitution :View Statutes : Online Sunshine|work=state.fl.us}}</ref> |---- |'''[[List of individuals executed in Georgia|Georgia]] |Trial Court Judge |The court shall specify the time period for the execution in the sentence. The time period for the execution fixed by the court shall be seven days in duration and shall commence at noon on a specified date and shall end at noon on a specified date. The time period shall commence not less than 20 days nor more than 60 days from the date of sentencing. A new time period for the execution -due to stay- fixed by the judge shall commence not less than ten nor more than 20 days from the date of the order.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lexis-nexis.com/hottopics/gacode/default.asp|title=LexisNexis® Custom Solution: Georgia Code Research Tool|work=lexis-nexis.com}}</ref> |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in Idaho|Idaho]] |Trial Court Judge | |---- |'''[[List of individuals executed in Illinois|Illinois]] |[[Supreme Court of Illinois]] |'''The death penalty in Illinois was repealed in 2011.''' |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in Indiana|Indiana]] |[[Supreme Court of Indiana]] | |---- |'''[[List of individuals executed in Kansas|Kansas]]''' | |'''No executions have occurred in Kansas since 1965.''' |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in Kentucky|Kentucky]]''' |[[Governor of Kentucky|Governor]] |The execution shall in theory be carried out on the fifth Friday following the affirmation of the sentence by the [[Kentucky Supreme Court]]. However, if the sentence is not carried out because of stays or any other cause, the governor may appoint another day of execution and may continue to do so until the sentence is carried into effect.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lrc.state.ky.us/KRS/431-00/CHAPTER.HTM|title=Kentucky Revised Statutes - Chapter 431|work=state.ky.us}}</ref> |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in Louisiana|Louisiana]]''' |Trial Court Judge | |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in Maryland|Maryland]] |Trial Court Judge |'''Maryland's death penalty was repealed May 2, 2013 for all future trials. The governor commuted the sentences of the four remaining members of death row to life without parole on December 31, 2014.''' |---- |'''[[Massachusetts]] |Trial Court Judge |'''Death penalty statute found unconstitutional in 1984'''- [http://law.justia.com/massachusetts/codes/gl-pt4-toc/279-57.html Section 57 - chapter 279] |---- |'''[[List of individuals executed in Mississippi|Mississippi]] |[[Supreme Court of Mississippi]] | |---- |'''[[List of individuals executed in Missouri|Missouri]] |[[Supreme Court of Missouri]] | |---- |'''[[List of individuals executed in Montana|Montana]] |Trial Court Judge | |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in Nebraska|Nebraska]] |[[Nebraska Supreme Court]] | |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in Nevada|Nevada]] |Trial Court Judge | |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in New Hampshire|New Hampshire]] |Governor |The governor and council or their designee shall determine the time of performing such execution . |---- |'''[[List of individuals executed in New Mexico|New Mexico]] |Trial Court Judge |When judgment of death is rendered by any court of competent jurisdiction a warrant signed by the judge and attested by the clerk under the seal of the court must be drawn and delivered to the sheriff. It must state the conviction and judgment and appoint a day on which the judgment is to be executed, which must be not less than sixty nor more than ninety days from the date of judgment and must direct the sheriff to deliver the defendant, at a time specified in said order, not more than ten days from the date of judgment, to the warden of the state penitentiary at Santa Fe for execution <ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.justia.com/newmexico/codes/nmrc/jd_31-14-1-d02b.html|title=Section 31-14-1 — Warrant of execution upon judgment of death; time of execution. :: Article 14 — Execution of Death Sentence, 31-14-1 through 31-14-16. :: Chapter 31 — Criminal Procedure. :: 2006 New Mexico Statutes :: New Mexico Statutes :: US Codes and Statutes :: US Law :: Justia|work=Justia Law}}</ref> |---- |'''[[List of individuals executed in New York|New York]] |Trial Court Judge |'''Death penalty abolished in 2007''' The week of execution appointed in the warrant shall be not less than 30 days and not more than 60 days after the issuance of the warrant. The date of execution within said week shall be left to the discretion of the commissioner, but the date and hour of the execution shall be announced publicly no later than seven days prior to said execution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.justia.com/newyork/codes/correction/cor0651_651.html|title=Time Of Execution. :: The Death Penalty :: Correction :: 2006 New York Code :: New York Code :: US Codes and Statutes :: US Law :: Justia|work=Justia Law}}</ref> |---- |'''[[List of individuals executed in North Carolina|North Carolina]] | | |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in Ohio|Ohio]] |[[Supreme Court of Ohio]] | |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in Oklahoma|Oklahoma]] |[[Oklahoma Court of Criminal Appeals]] |[http://law.justia.com/oklahoma/codes/os22.html code of criminal procedure of the State of Oklahoma, §221001]{{Clarify|date=May 2017}} |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in Oregon|Oregon]] |Trial Court Judge | |---- |'''[[List of individuals executed in Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania]] |[[Governor of Pennsylvania|Governor]] |[https://web.archive.org/web/20041009223422/http://www.cor.state.pa.us/portal/lib/portal/Warrants_by_Governor.pdf List of execution Warrants Issued since 1985] At least 349 execution warrants were signed since 1985, but only three executions were carried out, because those three defendants waived appeals. |---- |'''[[List of individuals executed in South Carolina|South Carolina]] |[[South Carolina Supreme Court]] | |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in South Dakota|South Dakota]] |Trial Court Judge | |---- |'''[[List of individuals executed in Tennessee|Tennessee]] |[[Tennessee Supreme Court]] | |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in Texas|Texas]] |Trial Court Judge |The first execution date may not be earlier than the 91st day after the date the convicting court enters the order setting the execution date. A subsequent execution date may not be earlier than the 31st day after the date the convicting court enters the order setting the execution date. The execution date shall be a Tuesday, Wednesday or Thursday. |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in Utah|Utah]] |Trial Court Judge |The appointed day the judgment is to be executed, which may not be fewer than 30 days nor more than 60 days from the date of issuance of the warrant, and may not be a Sunday, Monday, or a legal holiday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://le.utah.gov/~code/TITLE77/htm/77_19_000600.htm|title=Utah State Legislature|work=utah.gov}}</ref> |---- |'''[[List of individuals executed in Virginia|Virginia]] |Trial Court Judge | |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in Washington|Washington]] |Trial Court Judge | '''Death penalty abolished in 2018''' |---- |'''[[Capital punishment in Wyoming|Wyoming]] |Trial Court Judge | |}
